metaclass.name: MetaClass
metaclass.description: A metaclass is a class whose instances are classes. Metaclasses are typically used to construct metamodels. The objects you create are stored in the repository in the metaclass corresponding to their types. Metaclasses are used in the explorer when searching for objects in the repository and when the metamodel is extended to include a new type of object. Example: message, org-unit, etc.

properties.name: Loggability
properties.description: This parameter defines for a MetaObject if updates will be logged in the transaction embedded logfile or not.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert. Possible values:?	Unloggable: U: updates are not logged (Be careful, your updates are also not dispatched !)?	Loggable     : L (default): updates are logged. Attention: this is an expert customization :1) A specific study should be made to evaluate the specific impacts of this change.MEGA is not commited to perform this study. It is the project responsibility.This change will not remove data from the existing logfile (object dispatched and logged before the change).2) To perform this change the user must be allowed to update MEGA data.A metamodel compilation must be performed to validate the change.3) Platform technical impactsIf data a regularily created for this MetaClass and if repository logfile is enabled-Repository size will increase more slowly. -Transaction dispatch performances will improve.4) Platform functional impactsFor each Metaclass where logging has been disabled, the following features will not be available:-Export of repository logfile from the Administration Console does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -Transaction backup logfile (external file) does not contain updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (tab General > History of objects) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -View object history (Menu File > Properties, tab  Updates ) does not display updates for this MetaClass. -Undo redo is not available for updates regarding this MetaClass. -In the window displayed when exiting MEGA, the button  Later  is not displayed if all updates are regarding this MetaClass?

properties.name: MetaLayer
properties.description: This parameter indicates if an object belongs to the metamodel layer or to the meta-metamodel layer of the MOF (Meta Object facility) architecture.Do not set a value for this property if you are not an expert.The MEGA Software environment is based on a four-layer architecture as standardized by the OMG:- M0: The information layer comprises data of the  real world  which the user describes using MEGA products. (e.g.  Alan Smith )- M1: The model layer comprises models that describe data in the information layer. Since MEGA software is a true modeling environment, we can say that this is the  MEGA world  (e.g.  Sales Director )- M2: The metamodel layer comprises several domain-specific metamodels. A metamodel is an  abstract language  defined to write models. A set of concepts relating to the domain being modeled. MEGA products provide an extensive collection of such metamodels, for example the UML metamodel, the workflow (BPMN) metamodel and the business process metamodel. These metamodels can be modified or extended to suit specific requirements.  Metamodel  is the default value and should be used for extensions. (e.g.  Org-Unit )- M3: The meta-metamodel layer comprises the  top level  metamodel required to describe any type of metamodel. The MEGA meta-metamodel complies with the MOF (Meta Object Facility) recommendations of the OMG. It is reflexive, i.e. able to define itself as well as any type of metamodel. MOF is a very high level standardized metamodel, modification of which we do not recommend. Conventionally, meta-meta-objects are prefixed  Meta . (e.g.  MetaClass )

One of the assigned Person (System) can then trigger the Workflow Transition to indicate that he she has performed the corresponding operation.

metaclass.name: WorkflowDefinition
metaclass.description: A Workflow Definition enables definition of a sequence of operations performed by MEGA users. When executed, the workflow (Workflow Instance) assures management of the sequence of operations and notification of the Person (System) involved. The workflow can be applied to a repository object known as the Workflow Subject. In this case, expected operations are related to this object.Formally, a Workflow Definition is represented in the form of a state machine comprising Workflow Status. The sequence of Workflow Status is expressed by linking these using Workflow Transition.At any given moment of Workflow Instance progress, one of the Workflow Definition Workflow Status is the current Workflow Status. Output Workflow Transition of this Workflow Status correspond to the different possible operations expected of participant Person (System).Person (System) participating in a Workflow Instance pass it from the current Workflow Status to the next by triggering the Workflow Transition corresponding to the operation performed by the Person (System).

properties.name: SubjectMandatory
properties.description: This property indicates that to instantiate a Workflow, the latter must be connected necessarily to a subject.

properties.name: AllowSubjectMetaClassListing
properties.description: This property allows display of a list in order to select a subject at workflow creation.

properties.name: AllowSubjectMetaClassQuery
properties.description: This property proposes the standard search of the subject at workflow creation.

properties.name: AllowSubjectMetaClassCreation
properties.description: This property allows creation of a subject at the creation of a workflow.

properties.name: ActiveWorkflowDefinition
properties.description: This property allows the use of a workflow. As long as its value is false, the workflow will not be instantiated.

properties.name: UniqueInstantiation
properties.description: This attribute allows you to specify that the object can be associated with only one instantiation of the workflow.

properties.name: InstantiateAtCreation
properties.description: This attribute allows to enable the instantiation of a workflow to the creation of the subject.

properties.name: MainWorkflow
properties.description: This property allows you to specify that the status of the subject is defined from this workflow.

metaclass.name: WorkflowStatus
metaclass.description: A Workflow Status corresponds to a step in progress of a workflow defined by a Workflow Definition. Interconnected by Workflow Transition, Workflow Status express the sequence of operations expected by Person (System) participating in a Workflow Instance. A Person (System) taking part in a Workflow Instance can trigger one of the output Workflow Transition of the current Workflow Status to inform that the operation expected of them has been performed.

properties.name: Name
properties.description: Short Name of the object (posibility to get the long name with an argument)

properties.name: UsersSelectionMode
properties.description: Users Selection Mode defines constraints applied to allocate the effective users associated to a Workflow Transition when the previous Transition de workflow is triggered.The set of users potentially allocated to a Workflow Status is defined by Workflow Participant to the corresponding Workflow Transition.Depending on the Users Selection Mode: - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - All: all users specified by the Workflow Participant are allocated to the next Workflow Transition without asking the current triggering user - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - Some: all users specified by the Workflow Participant are suggested to be allocated to the next Workflow Transition by asking the current triggering user to choose one or several users - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - One: the current triggering user chooses one user to associate to the next Workflow Transition among the set of users specified by the Workflow Participant

properties.name: WorkflowStatusType
properties.description: A workflow status type may be  Default ,  Initial  or  Final . Workflow status types  Initial  and  Final  are mandatory.

metaclass.name: WorkflowTransition
metaclass.description: A Workflow Transition connects a source Workflow Status to a target Workflow Status. A Person (System) associated with a Workflow Transition for a given Workflow Instance can trigger the Workflow Transition, passing the Workflow Instance  from the current source Workflow Status to the target Workflow Status, which then becomes the current status. By this action, the Person (System) informs that the operation expected of him has been executed.The set of Person (System) that can be assigned to the Workflow Transition  in the framework of execution of a Workflow Instance is defined on Workflow Participant connected to the Workflow Transition.

properties.name: Name
properties.description: Short Name of the object (posibility to get the long name with an argument)

properties.name: MultipleTransitionTriggering
properties.description: In the case Multiple Transition Triggering is specified, each user allocated to the Workflow Transition instance can trigger the transition.It enables each user filling in Workflow Transition attached information.After the next status becomes current, no more user can trigger the Workflow Transition.

properties.name: UsersSelectionMode
properties.description: Users Selection Mode defines constraints applied to allocate the effective users associated to a Workflow Transition when the previous Transition de workflow is triggered.The set of users potentially allocated to a Workflow Status is defined by Workflow Participant to the corresponding Workflow Transition.Depending on the Users Selection Mode: - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - All: all users specified by the Workflow Participant are allocated to the next Workflow Transition without asking the current triggering user - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - Some: all users specified by the Workflow Participant are suggested to be allocated to the next Workflow Transition by asking the current triggering user to choose one or several users - Workflow Transition Participant Mode - One: the current triggering user chooses one user to associate to the next Workflow Transition among the set of users specified by the Workflow Participant

properties.name: MassTransition
properties.description: When this attribute is selected then this transition can be triggered simultaneously for several instances of workflow.

properties.name: Proposeacomment
properties.description: Enables to enter a comment when triggering a workflow transition.

properties.name: WorkflowTransitionCode
properties.description: The Workflow Transition Code enables to specify a characters string which identifies a Workflow Transition within a Workflow Definition.Several Workflow Transition can share the same name in one Workflow Definition. The Workflow Transition Code enables differentiating those Workflow Transition, for example in configuration tools in which those Workflow Transition appear.

properties.name: WarningofTransition
properties.description: Enables to display a warning when triggering the workflow transition.

metaclass.description: An external reference allows you to associate an object with a document outside the repository. For example, you can create references to regulations concerning safety or the environment, legal issues, etc.  The location of this document can be indicated as a file path or Web page address using its URL (Universal Resource Locator).

properties.name: Accesspath
properties.description: An access path indicates what folder to use when creating a reference for an environment repository or a site environment. When all repositories are created in the same location as the environment, the path created at installation (the DB folder under the environment root) is sufficient and is given as the default. To save a repository to a folder other than that of the environment, you must declare a new access path.
